            {
                "Author": {
                    "ProfileUrl": "http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/AC6LV5D2RKTIR"
                },
                "Date": "on October 2, 2012",
                "Helpfulness": "",
                "StarRating": "4",
                "Text": "I have to say that as a physics nerd myself, I enjoyed this book. It can be considered \"light reading\" for people who regularly read about these subjects, but I thought that this book was presented in a new, refreshing way that kept me entertained. I enjoyed Al-Khalili's writing style, it was both informative and humourous, and didn't sound too childish or overbearing either. I feel like this book is refreshing in that it discusses some very old paradoxes in new, modern ways. My wife, who is a science nerd but isn't into physics as much as I am, enjoyed this book too. She found it easy to read and we ended up having a lot of interesting discussions regarding things contained in the book. I whoreheartedly recommend this for people new to physics and physics nerds as well."
            },
            {
                "Author": {
                    "ProfileUrl": "http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/ANSFRRLSKV39G"
                },
                "Date": "on September 21, 2012",
                "Helpfulness": "",
                "StarRating": "4",
                "Text": "I read this book over the course of a weekend, but have already referred back to it a couple of times when thinking about some of the paradoxes that Al-Khalili presented and discussed. I referred back because of some of the science or math he used to explain some of the theories.  As a bit of a physics geek, I really enjoyed the modern updates to the discussions about some of these very old physics quandaries. If you are a math or physics geek, you need to read this book. To talk about specific paradoxes and the outcomes in this book would be spoilers, so I won't do that. I will just give it a very enthusiastic thumbs up!"
            },
