            {
                "Author": {
                    "ProfileUrl": "http://www.amazon.com/gp/pdp/profile/A185QFJRTB5W93"
                },
                "Date": "on September 26, 2012",
                "Helpfulness": 0.0,
                "StarRating": "5",
                "Text": "Well, the title of this review kind of gets right to the point. This book was a fun read the entire way through. It should be mentioned that this is the opinion of a guy who \"borrowed\" Schrodinger's Cat  and A Brief History of Time from the school library as a kid (on several occassions). The author introduces the reader to some common paradoxes and a few I had personally never heard of before. He keeps the reading understandable as he builds on differing concepts in each consecutive chapter. I would not go as far to call this \"light physics\" (as the reader will need to have at least a basic understanding of certain issues to be able to keep up) but I certainly call it \"fun physics.\" This is one of those books that I will be holding onto for a long time and look forward to reading again when the contemplative mood strikes. I cannot reccommend this book highly enough. Embrace your inner scientistist and grab this book!"
